  "text": "We use bold lowercase letters x x x and m m m to denote one video frame and one optical flow frame, respectively. In particular, the bold lowercase letter h h h is denoted as the extracted latent feature. We employ the capital letter E to represent the encoding network and the capital letter G to represent the generating network. Besides, we use the curlicue letter L to represent the loss function. Formally, given a sequence of t frames from video X = {x x x 1 , x x x 2 , . . . , x x x t }, we aim to build a model for predicting the next k frames {x x x t+1 ,x x x t+2 , . . . ,x x x t+k } by learning the video frame representations. The network disentangles the information from input x x x into time-varying (motion) information h h h m and time-invariant (content) information h h h c by the motion encoder E m and content encoder E c respectively due to the spatial-temporal disentanglement strategy. However, many existing methods only consider the temporal information at the representation level and they [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] can not achieve reasonable results on certain scenarios. Inspired by the shuffle based self-supervised learning, the proposed SEE-Net shuffles sequence generation orders and the shuffle discriminator SD converges only if effective temporal information is extracted.",
